</section>
<section id="h3_000012" data-index="893">
<h3 data-index="894"><span class="red" data-index="895">The Recording Process Illustrated</span></h3>
<p data-index="896"><a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0010-1" href="#c03-fig-0010" data-index="897" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0010" data-target-data-index="901"><b data-index="898">Illustrations 3.10</b></a> through <a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0019-1" href="#c03-fig-0019" data-index="899" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0019" data-target-data-index="1014"><b data-index="900">3.19</b></a> show the basic steps in the recording ­process, using the October transactions of Pioneer Advertising. Pioneer’s accounting period is a month. A basic analysis and a debit-credit analysis precede the journalizing and posting of each transaction. For simplicity, we use the T-account form in the illustrations instead of the standard account form.</p>
<figure id="c03-fig-0010" data-index="901">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0046.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the basic steps of the recording and posting process for the following transaction: On October 1, C. R. Yazici invests $100,000 cash in an advertising company called Pioneer Advertising. The five steps are Basic Analysis, Equation Analysis, Debit Credit Analysis, Journal Entry, and Posting. The basic analysis is labeled as: The asset Cash increases $100,000; stockholders’ equity, specifically, Common Stock, increases $100,000. The equation analysis step displays the transaction analysis format which begins with the accounting equation expressed as: Assets = Liabilities + owner's Equity. Cash is displayed as a $100,000 increase under the assets column, and as a $100,000 increase under stockholders' equity as common stock for the issued shares. 
The debit credit analysis step indicates: Debits increase assets: debit Cash $100,000; and credits increase stockholder's equity: credit common stock $100,000. The journal entry is displayed in general journal form with the date as October 1. The debit part of the transaction shows Cash with 100,000 in the debit column and the reference number of 101. Just below slightly indented, Common Stock is displayed with 311 as the reference, and 100,000 in the credit column. The description reads: Issued shares
for cash. Finally, the posting section shows a 100,000 amount posted to the debit side of the cash t-account, and 100,000 posted to the credit side of the common stock t-account, both dated as October 1. 
" data-index="902" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A777%2C%22height%22%3A679%7D">
<figcaption data-index="903"><p data-index="904"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="905"><b data-index="906"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-0010-1" data-index="907" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0010-1" data-target-data-index="897"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="908">ILLUSTRATION 3.10</span></a></b> <b data-index="909">Investment of Cash by Stockholders</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<figure id="c03-fig-0011" data-index="910">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0047.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the basic steps of the recording and posting process for the following transaction: On October 1, Pioneer Advertising purchases office equipment
costing $50,000 by signing a 3-month, 12 percent, $50,000 note payable.
The basic analysis is labeled as: The asset Equipment increases $50,000, the liability Notes Payable increases by $50,000. 
The equation analysis step displays the transaction analysis format. A $50,000 increase is shown under the assets column as Equipment, along with an increase of the same amount for notes payable under the liabilities column.
The debit credit analysis step indicates: Debits increase assets: debit Equipment $5,000; and credits increase liabilities: credit Notes Payable $50,000. 
The journal entry is displayed in general journal form with the date as October 1. The debit part of the transaction is recorded by displaying the account name, Equipment, with 50,000 in the debit column and a reference to 157. Just below, Notes payable is displayed with 50,000 in the credit column with a reference of 200. The description reads: Issued 3-month, 12% note for office equipment. Finally, the posting section shows a 50,000 amount posted to the debit side of the equipment t-account, and 50,000 posted to the credit side of the Notes Payable t-account, both dated as October 1.
" data-index="911" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A777%2C%22height%22%3A572%7D">
<figcaption data-index="912"><p data-index="913"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-14" id="Page_3-14" data-index="914"></span><span class="figureLabel" data-index="915"><b data-index="916"><a role="doc-backlink" data-index="917"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="918">ILLUSTRATION 3.11</span></a></b> <b data-index="919">Purchase of Office Equipment</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<figure id="c03-fig-0012" data-index="920">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0048.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the basic steps of the recording and posting process for the following transaction: On October 2, Pioneer Advertising receives a $12,000 cash advance from R. Knox, a client, for advertising services that are expected to be completed by December 31. The basic analysis is labeled as: The asset Cash increases $12,000; the liability Unearned Service Revenue increases $12,000 because the service has not been performed yet. That is, when Pioneer receives an advance payment, it should record an unearned revenue, a liability, in order to recognize the obligation that exists. Note also that although many liabilities have the word “payable” in their title, unearned revenue is considered a liability because the liability is satisfied by providing a product or performing a service. 
The equation analysis step displays cash with a $12,000 increase under the assets column, along with unearned service revenue as a $12,000 increase under the liabilities column.
The debit credit analysis step indicates: Debits increase assets: debit Cash $12,000; Credits increase liabilities: credit Unearned Service Revenue $12,000. 
The journal entry shows the date as October 2. The debit part of the transaction is recorded by displaying the account name, Cash, with 12,000 in the debit column and a reference of 101. Just below, Unearned Service Revenue is displayed with a reference of 209 and 12,000 in the credit column. The description reads: Received cash from R. Knox for future service. Finally, the posting section shows a 12,000 debit posted to the cash t-account and to the credit side of the Unearned Service Revenue t-account, dated as October 2.
" data-index="921" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A777%2C%22height%22%3A721%7D">
<figcaption data-index="922"><p data-index="923"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="924"><b data-index="925"><a role="doc-backlink" data-index="926"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="927">ILLUSTRATION 3.12</span></a></b> <b data-index="928">Receipt of Cash for Future Service</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<figure id="c03-fig-0013" data-index="929">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0049.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the basic steps of the recording and posting process for the following transaction: On October 3, Pioneer pays office rent for October in cash of $9,000. The basic analysis reads: Rent Expense increases $9,000 because the payment pertains only to the current month; the asset Cash decreases $9,000. 
The equation analysis step displays cash as a $9,000 decrease under the assets column, along with Rent Expense as a $9,000 decrease under the stockholder's equity column. The debit credit analysis step indicates: Debits increase expenses: debit Rent Expense $9,000; and credits decrease assets: credit Cash $9,000. 
The journal entry is displayed in general journal form with the date as October 3. The debit part of the transaction is recorded by displaying the account name, Rent Expense, with a reference to 729 and $9,000 in the debit column. Just below, Cash is displayed with a reference to 101 and $9,000 in the credit column. The description is next as: Paid October rent. 
Finally, the posting section shows the two previous cash transactions along with the current $9,000 amount posted as a credit in the cash t-account, and $9,000 posted as a debit to the Rent Expense t-account, both dated as October 3.
" data-index="930" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A777%2C%22height%22%3A587%7D">
<figcaption data-index="931">
<p data-index="932"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-15" id="Page_3-15" data-index="933"></span><span class="figureLabel" data-index="934"><b data-index="935"><a role="doc-backlink" data-index="936"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="937">ILLUSTRATION 3.13</span></a></b> <b data-index="938">Payment of Monthly Rent</b></span></p>
</figcaption>
</figure>
<figure id="c03-fig-0014" data-index="939">
