The equation analysis step displays the transaction analysis format with cash as a $6,000 decrease under the assets column, along with Prepaid Insurance as a $6,000 increase under the assets column.
The debit credit analysis step indicates: Debits increase assets: debit Prepaid Insurance $6,000; and credits decrease assets: credit Cash $6,000. 
The journal entry is dated as October 4. Prepaid Insurance is displayed with a reference of 130 and 6,000 in the debit column. Just below, Cash is displayed with a reference to 101, and 6,000 in the credit column. The description reads: Paid one-year policy;
effective date October 1. Finally, the postings to the cash account are carried forward to this illustration, and the current posting shows a 6,000 amount posted to the credit side of the cash t-account, and 6,000 posted to the credit side of the Prepaid Insurance t-account, both dated as October 4.
