</figure>
<figure id="c03-fig-0019" data-index="1014">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0055.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the basic steps of the recording and posting process for the following transaction: On October 31, Pioneer Advertising receives $28,000 in cash and bills Copa Company $72,000 for advertising services of $100,000 performed in October. The basic analysis reads: The asset Cash increases $28,000; the asset Accounts Receivable increases $72,000; the revenue account Service Revenue increases $100,000. The equation analysis step displays Cash as an increase of $28,000 and Accounts Receivable as an increase of $72,000 under the Assets section, along with an increase of $100,000 under the Stockholders' Equity section for Service Revenue. The debit credit analysis step indicates: Debits increase assets: debit Cash $28,000 and Accounts Receivable $72,000. Credits increase revenues: credit Service Revenue $100,000. 
The journal entry is dated as October 31, and displays the Cash account with a reference to 101 and 10,000 in the debit column, followed by the Accounts Receivable account with a reference of 112 and $72,000 in the debit column. The Service Revenue account is on the next line, with a reference to 400 and 100,000 in the credit column. Finally, the Posting section shows the journal entry posted to the Cash and Service Revenue t-accounts. The Cash t-account postings are carried forward from previous illustrations, and the current posting of 28,000 is posted as a debit. The Accounts Receivable t-account displays a posting on the debit side dated October 31 in the amount of 72,000. The Service Revenue t-account displays a credit posting dated October 31 for 100,000.
" data-index="1015" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A777%2C%22height%22%3A724%7D">
<figcaption data-index="1016"><p data-index="1017"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-18" id="Page_3-18" data-index="1018"></span><span class="figureLabel" data-index="1019"><b data-index="1020"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-0019-1" data-index="1021" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0019-1" data-target-data-index="899"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="1022">ILLUSTRATION 3.19</span></a></b> <b data-index="1023">Receipt of Cash for Services Provided</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="1024">Study these transaction analyses carefully. <b data-index="1025">The purpose of transaction analysis is first to identify the type of account involved, and then to determine whether to make a debit or a credit to the account.</b> You should always perform this type of analysis before preparing a journal entry. Doing so will help you understand the journal entries discussed in this chapter as well as more complex journal entries in later chapters.</p>
</section>
<section id="h3_000013" data-index="1026">
<h3 data-index="1027"><span class="red" data-index="1028">Trial Balance</span></h3>
<p data-index="1029">A <span class="glossTerm" data-index="1030"><span class="blue" data-index="1031"><b data-index="1032">trial balance</b></span></span> is a list of accounts and their balances at a given time. A company usually prepares a trial balance at the end of an accounting period. The trial balance lists the accounts in the order in which they appear in the ledger, with debit balances listed in the left column and credit balances in the right column. The totals of the two columns must agree.</p>
<p data-index="1033">The trial balance proves the mathematical equality of debits and credits after posting. Under the double-entry system, this equality occurs when the sum of the debit  account balances equals the sum of the credit account balances. A trial balance also  uncovers errors in journalizing and posting. In addition, it is useful in the preparation of financial statements. The procedures for preparing a trial balance consist of:</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="1034"><span class="label" data-index="1035"><b data-index="1036">1.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Listing the account titles and their balances.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="1037"><span class="label" data-index="1038"><b data-index="1039">2.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Totaling the debit and credit columns.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="1040"><span class="label" data-index="1041"><b data-index="1042">3.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Proving the equality of the two columns.</p>
<p data-index="1043"><a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0020-1" href="#c03-fig-0020" data-index="1044" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0020" data-target-data-index="1046"><b data-index="1045">Illustration 3.20</b></a> presents the trial balance prepared from the ledger of Pioneer Advertising. Note that the total debits ($287,000) equal the total credits ($287,000). A trial balance also often shows account numbers to the left of the account titles.</p>
<figure id="c03-fig-0020" data-index="1046">
<table style=" border: 1px solid #000; background-color: #F8F7EA;" data-index="1047">
<thead data-index="1048">
<tr data-index="1049">
<td colspan="7" data-index="1050"><span class="center bdr1" data-index="1051">Pioneer Advertising<br data-index="1052">Trial Balance<br data-index="1053">October 31, 2020</span></td>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody data-index="1054">
<tr data-index="1055">
