<figcaption data-index="1839"><p data-index="1840"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="1841"><b data-index="1842"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-0033-1" data-index="1843" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0033-1" data-target-data-index="1791"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="1844">ILLUSTRATION 3.33</span></a></b> <b data-index="1845">Adjustment for Salaries and Wages Expense</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="1846">After this adjustment, the balance in Salaries and Wages Expense of $46,000 (23 days <span class="mathpi1" data-index="1847">×</span> $2,000) is the actual salaries and wages expense for October. The balance in Salaries and Wages Payable of $6,000 is the amount of the liability for salaries and wages owed as of October 31. <b data-index="1848">Without the $6,000 adjustment for salaries, both Pioneer’s expenses and liabilities are understated by $6,000.</b></p>
<p data-index="1849"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-29" id="Page_3-29" data-index="1850"></span>Pioneer pays salaries and wages every four weeks. Consequently, the next payday is November 23, when it will again pay total salaries and wages of $40,000. The payment consists of $6,000 of salaries and wages payable at October 31 plus $34,000 of salaries and wages expense for November (17 working days as shown in the November calendar <span class="mathpi1" data-index="1851">×</span> $2,000). Therefore, Pioneer makes the following entry on November 23.</p>
