<p data-index="1930">This entry eliminates the liability for Salaries and Wages Payable that Pioneer recorded in the October 31 adjusting entry. This entry also records the proper amount of Salaries and Wages Expense for the period between November 1 and November 23.</p>
</section>
<section data-index="1931">
<h5 class="grey" data-index="1932">Bad Debts</h5>
<p data-index="1933">Companies estimate uncollectible accounts at the end of each period. This ensures that receivables are reported on the balance sheet at their net realizable value. As a result, proper valuation of the receivable balance requires recognition of uncollectible receivables and an adjusting entry for bad debt expense.</p>
<figure data-index="1934">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0075.jpg" alt="An illustration titled “Bad Debts” shows a man standing with hands spread out and cash flowing around. The text at the bottom reads, “October 31: Uncollectible accounts; record bad debt expense”." data-index="1935" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A227%2C%22height%22%3A277%7D">
</figure>
<p data-index="1936">At the end of each period, a company such as <span class="red" data-index="1937"><b data-index="1938">General Mills</b></span> estimates the amount of receivables that will later prove to be uncollectible. General Mills bases the estimate on various factors: the amount of bad debts it experienced in past years, general economic conditions, how long the receivables are past due, and other factors that indicate the extent of uncollectibility. To illustrate, assume that, based on past experience, Pioneer Advertising reasonably estimates a bad debt expense for the month of $1,600. The analysis and adjustment process for bad debts is summarized in <a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0034-1" href="#c03-fig-0034" data-index="1939" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0034" data-target-data-index="1941"><b data-index="1940">Illustration 3.34</b></a>.</p>
<figure id="c03-fig-0034" data-index="1941">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0076.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the transaction to record the adjustment for bad debt expense. The basic analysis reads: The expense Bad Debt Expense is increased $1,600, and the contra asset Allowance for Doubtful Accounts is increased $1,600. The equation analysis displays the following effects: Under Assets, negative $6,000 for Allowance for Doubtful Accounts; and under Stockholders' Equity, Bad Debt Expense, negative $1,600. The Debit Credit Analysis reads: Debits increase expenses: debit Bad Debt Expense $1,600. Credits increase contra assets: credit Allowance for Doubtful Accounts $1,600.
The journal entry is dated October 31. The account Bad Debt Expense is displayed with a reference to 910 and as 1,600 in the debit column, and Allowance for Doubtful Accounts displayed just below with a reference to 113, and as 1,600 in the credit column. The description appears on the last line as: To record monthly bad debt expense.
Three t-accounts are displayed in the posting section. The Accounts Receivable account shows a posting of 72,000 on October 2 and the October 31 entry of 2,000, both posted on the debit side. The 74,000 balance on October 31 is posted on the debit side. The Allowance for Doubtful Accounts t-account shows the October 31 adjustment of 1,600 on the credit side, followed by the balance as 1,600 on October 31 on the credit side as well. The Bad Debt Expense t-account shows the October 31 adjustment of 1,600 on the debit side, followed by the balance as 1,600 on October 31 on the debit side as well.
" data-index="1942" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A777%2C%22height%22%3A580%7D">
