<br data-index="2150"><hr data-index="2151">
<section id="h2_0006" data-index="2152">
<h2 data-index="2153"><span class="blue" data-index="2154">Preparing Financial Statements</span></h2>
<aside data-index="2155">
<div class="top hr" data-index="2156"><hr data-index="2157"></div>
<section class="feature1" style=" background-color: #e2f4fd;" data-index="2158">
<h3 id="h3_0004" data-index="2159"><span class="red" data-index="2160">LEARNING OBJECTIVE 4</span></h3>
<p data-index="2161">Prepare financial statements from the adjusted trial balance and prepare closing ­entries.</p>
<div class="bottom hr" data-index="2162"><hr data-index="2163"></div>
</section>
</aside>
<p data-index="2164">As indicated above, <b data-index="2165">Pioneer Advertising can prepare financial statements directly from the adjusted trial balance.</b> <a href="#c03-fig-0036" data-index="2166" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0036" data-target-data-index="2171">Illustrations 3.36</a> and <a href="#c03-fig-0037" data-index="2167" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0037" data-target-data-index="2184">3.37</a> show the interrelationships of data in the adjusted trial balance and the financial statements.</p>
<p data-index="2168">As <a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0036-1" href="#c03-fig-0036" data-index="2169" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0036" data-target-data-index="2171"><b data-index="2170">Illustration 3.36</b></a> shows, Pioneer prepares the income statement from the revenue and expense accounts. Next, it derives the retained earnings statement from the retained earnings and dividends accounts and the net income (or net loss) shown in the income statement.</p>
<figure id="c03-fig-0036" data-index="2171">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0078.jpg" alt="An illustration shows the adjusted trial balance along with the income statement and the retained earnings statement. The adjusted trial balance begins with a three-line heading consisting of the name of the company, Pioneer Advertising, type of statement, adjusted trial balance, and the date, October 31, 2020.  The table is divided into three columns, with column headings marked from left to right as: Account, Debit, and Credit. The account names and their respected balances are as follows:
Cash: 80,000 debit; Accounts receivable: 74,000 debit; Allowance for doubtful accounts: 1,600 credit; Supplies: 10,000 debit; Prepaid insurance: 5,500 debit; Equipment: 50,000 debit; Accumulated depreciation, equipment: 400 credit; Notes Payable: 50,000 credit; Accounts Payable: 25,000 credit; Unearned Service Revenue: 8,000 credit; Salaries and Wages Payable: 6,000 credit; Interest Payable: 500 credit; Common Stock: 100,000 credit; Retained Earnings: 0 credit; Dividends: 5,000 debit; Service Revenue: 106,000 credit; Salaries and Wages Expense: 46,000 debit; Supplies Expense: 15,500 debit; Rent Expense: 9,000 debit; Insurance Expense: 500 debit; Interest Expense: 500 debit; Depreciation Expense: 400 debit; Bad Debt Expense: 1,600 debit. The total debits are equal to the total credits and displayed as $297,500.
The Income statement begins with a three-line heading consisting of the name of the company, Pioneer Advertising, type of statement, income statement, and the period, For the Month Ending October 31, 2020. There are arrows pointing from the respective account balances on the trial balance to those that are reported on the income statement, revenues and expenses. The revenues section of the income statement shows Service Revenue of $106,000. In the Expenses section of the income statement, each of the expense accounts are listed with their respective amounts as Salaries and Wages Expense: 46,000 debit; Supplies Expense: 15,500 debit; Rent Expense: 9,000 debit; Insurance Expense: 500 debit; Interest Expense: 500 debit; Depreciation Expense: 400 debit; and Bad Debt Expense: 1,600 debit.  Total expenses on the income statement are $73,000. Expenses are subtracted from revenues arriving at net income of $33,000.  
       The retained earnings statement begins with a three-line heading consisting of the name of the company, Pioneer Advertising; type of statement, retained earnings statement, and the period, For the Month Ending October 31, 2020. There are arrows pointing from the retained earnings and dividends account balances and from net income on the income statement, to the respective line items on the retained earnings statement. The retained earnings statement displays the following: Retained earnings, October 1: $0; Add Net income: 33,000; followed by a subtotal of 33,000; Less Dividends: 5,000; and Retained earnings, October 31 as $28,000.
An arrow from retained earnings on October 31 of $28,000 point towards right depicting transfer to the balance sheet on the next illustration.
" data-index="2172" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A1026%2C%22height%22%3A840%7D">
<figcaption data-index="2173"><p data-index="2174"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="2175"><b data-index="2176"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-0036-1" data-index="2177" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0036-1" data-target-data-index="2169"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="2178">ILLUSTRATION 3.36</span></a></b> <b data-index="2179">Preparation of the Income Statement and Retained Earnings Statement from the Adjusted Trial Balance</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="2180"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-31" id="Page_3-31" data-index="2181"></span>As <a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0037-1" href="#c03-fig-0037" data-index="2182" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0037" data-target-data-index="2184"><b data-index="2183">Illustration 3.37</b></a> shows, Pioneer then prepares the balance sheet from the asset and liability accounts, the common stock account, and the ending retained earnings balance as reported in the retained earnings statement.</p>
<figure id="c03-fig-0037" data-index="2184">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0079.jpg" alt="The adjusted trial balance from the previous illustration is reproduced here along with the balance sheet. 
The balance sheet begins with a three-line heading consisting of the name of the company, Pioneer Advertising, type of statement, balance sheet, and the date, October 31, 2020. There are arrows pointing from the respective asset, liability, and stockholders' equity account balances on the trial balance to the amounts on the balance sheet to illustrate the preparation of the balance sheet. The assets section of the balance sheet display the names of all of the asset accounts and their respective balances, in the following amounts: Cash: $80,000; Accounts receivable: $74,000; Less Allowance for doubtful accounts: 1,600, with a net amount of 72,400; Supplies: 10,000; Prepaid insurance: 5,500; Equipment: 50,000; Less Accumulated depreciation equipment: 400 followed by the difference between the $50,000 cost and the accumulated depreciation of 400 for a net amount shown as 49,600.
The assets are totaled and displayed as total assets of $217,500. 
       The liabilities section of the balance sheet displays the following: Notes payable: $50,000; Accounts payable: 25,000; Unearned service revenue: 8,000; Salaries and wages payable: 6,000; and Interest payable: 500. The liabilities are totaled and displayed as total liabilities in the amount of $89,500.
     The stockholders’ equity section of the balance sheet shows common stock of 100,000, and retained earnings of 28,000. This amount is the balance at October 31, from the retained earnings statement. Finally, total liabilities and stockholders’ equity are totaled at $217,500.
" data-index="2185" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A1026%2C%22height%22%3A704%7D">
<figcaption data-index="2186"><p data-index="2187"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="2188"><b data-index="2189"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-0037-1" data-index="2190" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0037-1" data-target-data-index="2182"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="2191">ILLUSTRATION 3.37</span></a></b> <b data-index="2192">Preparation of the Balance Sheet from the Adjusted Trial Balance</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<section id="h3_000018" data-index="2193">
<h3 data-index="2194"><span class="red" data-index="2195">Closing</span></h3>
<p data-index="2196">The <span class="glossTerm" data-index="2197"><span class="blue" data-index="2198"><b data-index="2199">closing process</b></span></span> reduces the balance of nominal (temporary) accounts to zero in order to prepare the accounts for the next period’s transactions. In the closing process, Pioneer Advertising transfers all of the revenue and expense account balances (income statement items) to a clearing or suspense account called Income Summary. The Income Summary account matches revenues and expenses.</p>
<p data-index="2200">Pioneer uses this clearing account only at the end of each accounting period. The account represents the net income or net loss for the period. It then transfers this amount (the net income or net loss) to a stockholders’ equity account. (For a corporation, the stockholders’ equity account is retained earnings; for proprietorships and partnerships, it is a capital account.) Companies post all such <span class="glossTerm" data-index="2201"><span class="blue" data-index="2202"><b data-index="2203">closing entries</b></span></span> to the appropriate general ledger accounts.</p>
<section data-index="2204">
<h4 data-index="2205"><span class="codeColorBlue2" data-index="2206">Closing Entries</span></h4>
<p data-index="2207">In practice, companies generally prepare closing entries only at the end of a company’s annual accounting period. However, to illustrate the journalizing and posting of closing entries, we <span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-32" id="Page_3-32" data-index="2208"></span>will assume that Pioneer Advertising closes its books monthly. <a class="blue" id="c03-fig-0038-1" href="#c03-fig-0038" data-index="2209" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-0038" data-target-data-index="2211"><b data-index="2210">Illustration 3.38</b></a> shows the closing entries at October 31.</p>
