<td class="rline" data-index="4399"><span class="right" data-index="4400"><span class="red" data-index="4401">5,000</span></span></td>
<td data-index="4402"></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="4403">
<td class="rline" data-index="4404"></td>
<td class="rline" data-index="4405"></td>
<td class="rline" data-index="4406"></td>
<td class="rline" data-index="4407"></td>
<td class="rline" data-index="4408"></td>
<td class="rline" data-index="4409"> <span class="red" data-index="4410">Supplies</span></td>
<td class="rline" data-index="4411"></td>
<td data-index="4412"><span class="right" data-index="4413"><span class="red" data-index="4414">5,000</span></span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<figcaption data-index="4415"><p data-index="4416"><span class="figureLabel" data-index="4417"><b data-index="4418"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-1102-1" data-index="4419" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-1102-1" data-target-data-index="4266"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="4420">ILLUSTRATION 3B.2</span></a></b> <b data-index="4421">Comparison of Entries for Deferrals, with and without Reversing Entries</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p data-index="4422">After the adjusting entry on December 31 (regardless of whether using reversing entries), the asset account Supplies shows a balance of $5,000, and Supplies Expense shows a balance of $15,000. If the company initially debits Supplies Expense when it purchases the supplies, it then makes a reversing entry to return to the expense account the cost of unconsumed supplies. The company then continues to debit Supplies Expense for additional purchases of supplies during the next period.</p>
<p data-index="4423">Deferrals are generally entered in real accounts (assets and liabilities), thus making reversing entries unnecessary. This approach is used because it is advantageous for items that a company needs to apportion over several periods (e.g., supplies and parts inventories). However, for other items that do not follow this regular pattern and that may or may not involve two or more periods, a company ordinarily enters them initially in revenue or expense accounts. The revenue and expense accounts may not require adjusting, and the company thus systematically closes them to Income Summary.</p>
<p data-index="4424">Using the nominal accounts adds consistency to the accounting system. It also makes the recording more efficient, particularly when a large number of such transactions occur during the year. For example, the bookkeeper knows to expense invoice items (except for capital asset acquisitions). He or she need not worry whether an item will result in a prepaid expense at the end of the period because the company will make adjustments at the end of the period.</p>
</section>
<br data-index="4425"><hr data-index="4426">
<section id="h2_0014" data-index="4427">
<h2 data-index="4428"><span class="blue" data-index="4429">Summary of Reversing Entries</span></h2>
<p data-index="4430">We summarize guidelines for reversing entries as follows.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="4431"><span class="label" data-index="4432"><b data-index="4433">1.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> All accruals should be reversed.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="4434"><span class="label" data-index="4435"><b data-index="4436">2.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> All deferrals for which a company debited or credited the original cash transaction to an expense or revenue account should be reversed.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="4437"><span class="label" data-index="4438"><b data-index="4439">3.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Adjusting entries for depreciation and bad debts are not reversed.</p>
<p data-index="4440">Recognize that reversing entries do not have to be used. Therefore, some accountants avoid them entirely.</p>
</section>
<br data-index="4441">
<section id="h2_0015" data-index="4442">
<h2 data-index="4443"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-46" id="Page_3-46" data-index="4444"></span><span style=" padding: 10px; background-color: #B11116; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="4445">&nbsp;&nbsp;APPENDIX 3C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=" padding: 10px; background-color: #043D5D; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="4446">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Using a Worksheet: The Accounting Cycle Revisited&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></h2>
<br data-index="4447">
<aside data-index="4448">
<div class="top hr" data-index="4449"><hr data-index="4450"></div>
<section class="feature1" style=" background-color: #e2f4fd;" data-index="4451">
<h3 id="h3_0008" data-index="4452"><span class="red" data-index="4453">LEARNING OBJECTIVE *8</span></h3>
<p data-index="4454">Prepare a 10-column worksheet.</p>
<div class="bottom hr" data-index="4455"><hr data-index="4456"></div>
</section>
</aside>
<p data-index="4457">In this appendix, we provide an additional illustration of the end-of-period steps in the accounting cycle and illustrate the use of a worksheet (usually in an electronic spreadsheet) in this process. Using a <span class="glossTerm" data-index="4458"><span class="blue" data-index="4459"><b data-index="4460">worksheet</b></span></span> (spreadsheet) often facilitates the end-of-period (monthly, quarterly, or annually) accounting and reporting process. Use of a worksheet helps a company prepare the financial statements on a more timely basis. How? With a worksheet; a company need not wait until it journalizes and posts the adjusting and closing entries.</p>
<p data-index="4461">A company prepares a worksheet either on columnar paper or within a computer spreadsheet. In either form, a company uses the worksheet to adjust account balances and to prepare financial statements.</p>
<p data-index="4462"><b data-index="4463">The worksheet does not replace the financial statements.</b> Instead, it is an informal device for accumulating and sorting information needed for the financial statements. Completing the worksheet provides considerable assurance that a company properly handled all of the details related to the end-of-period accounting and statement preparation. The 10-column worksheet in <a class="blue" id="c03-fig-1201-1" href="#c03-fig-1201" data-index="4464" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-1201" data-target-data-index="4476">Illustration 3C.1</a> provides columns for the first trial balance, adjustments, adjusted trial balance, income statement, and balance sheet.</p>
</section>
<br data-index="4465"><hr data-index="4466">
<section id="h2_0016" data-index="4467">
<h2 data-index="4468"><span class="blue" data-index="4469">Worksheet Columns</span></h2>
<section id="h3_000028" data-index="4470">
<h3 data-index="4471"><span class="red" data-index="4472">Trial Balance Columns</span></h3>
<p data-index="4473">Uptown Cabinet Corp., shown in <a class="blue" href="#c03-fig-1201" data-index="4474" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-1201" data-target-data-index="4476"><b data-index="4475">Illustration 3C.1</b></a>, obtains data for the trial balance from its ledger balances at December 31. The amount for Inventory, $40,000, is the year-end inventory amount, which results from the application of a perpetual inventory system.</p>
<figure id="c03-fig-1201" data-index="4476">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c03/w0100.jpg" alt="A work sheet displays three-line heading consisting of name of the company, Uptown Cabinet Corporation; the type of statement, Ten-column worksheet; and the time period, For the year ended December 31, 2020. The worksheet is divided into six columns as: Account titles; Trial balance; Adjustments; Adjusted trial balance; Income statement; and Balance sheet. Each column, except account titles, is further divided into two sub-columns, debit and credit, with adjustments highlighted in red. The data presented in the table follows:
Cash shows a debit of 1,200 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Notes receivables shows a debit of 16,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Accounts receivable shows a debit of 41,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Allowance for doubtful accounts shows a credit of 2,000 in the trial balance column; a credit of 1,000 marked as A in the adjustments column; a credit of 3,000 in the adjusted trial balance and the balance sheet columns. 
Inventory shows a debit of 40,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Prepaid insurance shows a debit of 900 in the trial balance column; a credit of 360, marked as C in the adjustments column; and a debit of 540 in the adjusted trial balance and balance sheet columns. 
Equipment shows a debit of 67,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet column. 
Accumulated depreciation equipment shows a credit of 12,000 in the trial balance column; a credit of 6,700 marked as A in the adjustments column; a credit of 18,700 in the adjusted trial balance and the balance sheet columns. 
Notes payable shows a credit of 20,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Accounts payable shows a credit of 13,500 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns.
Bonds payable shows a credit of 30,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Common stock shows a credit of 50,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Retained earnings dated January 1, 2020 shows a credit of 16,200 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Dividends shows a debit of 2,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and balance sheet columns. 
Sales revenue shows a credit of 400,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns. 
Cost of goods sold shows a debit of 316,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns. 
Salaries and wages expense for sales shows a credit of 20,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns.
Advertising expense shows a credit of 10,200 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns. 
Salaries and wages expense for general shows a credit of 19,000 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns. Telephone and internet expense shows a credit of 600 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns. 
Rent expense shows a debit of 4,800 in the trial balance column; a credit of 500 marked as E in the adjustments column; and a debit of 4,300 in the adjusted trial balance and income statement columns. 
Property and tax expense shows a debit of 3,300 in the trial balance column; a debit of 2,000 marked as F in the adjustments column; adding to a debit of 5,300 in the adjusted trial balance and income statement columns. 
Interest expense shows  a debit of 1,700 in the trial balance, adjusted trial balance, and income statement columns. The total debit of trial balance columns is equal to the credit, displayed as $543,700.
Depreciation expense shows a debit of 6,700 marked as A in the adjustments column; and a debit of 6,700 in the adjusted trial balance and the income statement columns. 
Bad debt expense shows a debit of 1,000 marked as B in the adjustments column; and a debit of 1,000 in the adjusted trial balance and the income statement columns. 
Insurance expense shows a debit of 360 marked as C in the adjustments column; and a debit of 360 in the adjusted trial balance and the income statement columns. 
Interest receivable shows a debit of 800 marked as D in the adjustments column; a debit of 800 in the adjusted trial balance and the balance sheet columns. 
Interest revenue shows a credit of 800, marked as D in the adjustments column; a credit of 800 in the adjusted trial balance and the income statement columns. 
Prepaid rent shows a debit of 500 marked as E in the adjustments column; and a debit of 500 in the adjusted trial balance and balance sheet columns. 
Property taxes payable shows a credit of 2,000 marked as F in the adjustments; a credit of 2,000 in the adjusted trial balance and the balance sheet columns. 
Income tax expense shows a debit of 3,440 marked as G in the adjustments; and a debit of 3,440 in the adjusted trial balance and the income statement columns. 
Income taxes payable shows a credit of 3,440 marked as G in the adjustment; and a credit of 3,440 in the adjusted trial balance and the balance sheet columns. 
The total debits of the adjustments columns is equal to the total credits and displayed as $14,800. The total debits of the adjusted trial balance is equal to the total credits and displayed as $557,640. The subtotal of the debits of the income statement columns is $388,600 and $400,800 for the credits. The net income is the difference and appears as a debit of 12,200 in the income statement columns which results in total debits equal to the total credits in the amount of $400,800. The net income amount is added as a credit in the balance sheet columns resulting in the totals of the balance sheet columns being equal to each other in the amount of $169,040.
" data-index="4477" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A1022%2C%22height%22%3A1302%7D">
<figcaption data-index="4478"><p data-index="4479"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-47" id="Page_3-47" data-index="4480"></span><span class="figureLabel" data-index="4481"><b data-index="4482"><a role="doc-backlink" href="#c03-fig-1201-1" data-index="4483" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-1201-1" data-target-data-index="4464"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="4484">ILLUSTRATION 3C.1</span></a></b> <b data-index="4485">Use of a Worksheet</b></span></p></figcaption>
</figure>
</section>
<section id="h3_000029" data-index="4486">
<h3 data-index="4487"><span class="red" data-index="4488">Adjustments Columns</span></h3>
<p data-index="4489">After Uptown enters all adjustment data on the worksheet, it establishes the equality of the adjustment columns. It then extends the balances in all accounts to the adjusted trial balance columns.</p>
</section>
</section>
<br data-index="4490"><hr data-index="4491">
<section id="h2_0017" data-index="4492">
<h2 data-index="4493"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="3-48" id="Page_3-48" data-index="4494"></span><span class="blue" data-index="4495">Adjustments Entered on the Worksheet</span></h2>
<p data-index="4496">Items (a) through (g) below serve as the basis for the adjusting entries made in the worksheet for Uptown shown in <a href="#c03-fig-1201" data-index="4497" data-section-index="13" data-section-idref="c03-fig-1201" data-target-data-index="4476">Illustration 3C.1</a>.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4498"><span class="label" data-index="4499"><b data-index="4500">a.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Depreciation of equipment at the rate of 10 percent per year based on original cost of $67,000.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4501"><span class="label" data-index="4502"><b data-index="4503">b.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Estimated bad debts of $1,000, based on an aging of Accounts Receivable.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4504"><span class="label" data-index="4505"><b data-index="4506">c.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Insurance expired during the year $360.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4507"><span class="label" data-index="4508"><b data-index="4509">d.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Interest accrued on notes receivable as of December 31, $800.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4510"><span class="label" data-index="4511"><b data-index="4512">e.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> The Rent Expense account contains $500 rent paid in advance, which is applicable to next year.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4513"><span class="label" data-index="4514"><b data-index="4515">f.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Property taxes accrued December 31, $2,000.</p>
<p class="latin1" data-index="4516"><span class="label" data-index="4517"><b data-index="4518">g.</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Income taxes payable estimated $3,440.</p>
<p data-index="4519">The adjusting entries shown on the December 31, 2020, worksheet are as follows.</p>
<table data-index="4520">
